Note:
Runa Standard Library: Audio Effects Module

Provides comprehensive Digital Signal Processing (DSP) effects for audio manipulation.
Competitive with industry-standard libraries like JUCE, Web Audio API, and professional DAW plugins.

Features:
- Time-domain effects (delay, reverb, chorus, flanger)
- Frequency-domain effects (EQ, filters, spectral processing)
- Dynamics processing (compressor, limiter, gate, expander)
- Distortion and saturation effects
- Modulation effects (tremolo, vibrato, phaser)
- Spatial effects (stereo imaging, 3D positioning)
- Real-time processing with zero-latency monitoring
- Plugin architecture for custom effects
- GPU acceleration support for intensive processing
:End Note

Note: Core Audio Types and Constants
Type AudioSample is Float

Type called "AudioBuffer":
    samples as List[AudioSample]
    channels as Integer
    sample_rate as Integer
    length as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "AudioEffect":
    name as String
    parameters as Dictionary[String, Float]
    enabled as Boolean
    bypass as Boolean
    wet_dry_mix as Float defaults to 1.0
    input_gain as Float defaults to 1.0
    output_gain as Float defaults to 1.0
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type FilterType is:
    | LOW_PASS
    | HIGH_PASS
    | BAND_PASS
    | BAND_STOP
    | NOTCH
    | ALL_PASS
    | PEAK
    | LOW_SHELF
    | HIGH_SHELF

Type WindowType is:
    | HANNING
    | HAMMING
    | BLACKMAN
    | KAISER
    | RECTANGULAR
    | TRIANGULAR

Type CompressorMode is:
    | PEAK
    | RMS
    | PROGRAM_DEPENDENT

Type AudioProcessingResult is:
    | ProcessingSuccess with buffer as AudioBuffer
    | ProcessingError with message as String and code as String

Note: Audio Constants
Let NYQUIST_RATIO be 0.5
Let GOLDEN_RATIO be 1.618033988749
Let SQRT_2 be 1.4142135623731
Let LOG_10 be 2.302585092994
Let TWO_PI be 6.283185307179586
Let SAMPLE_RATES be list containing 8000, 11025, 16000, 22050, 44100, 48000, 88200, 96000, 176400, 192000

Note: Core Audio Buffer Operations
Process called "create_audio_buffer" that takes channels as Integer and sample_rate as Integer and length as Integer returns AudioBuffer:
    Let samples be list containing
    For i from 0 to channels times length minus 1:
        Add 0.0 to samples
    Return AudioBuffer with:
        samples as samples
        channels as channels
        sample_rate as sample_rate
        length as length
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "copy_audio_buffer" that takes buffer as AudioBuffer returns AudioBuffer:
    Let new_samples be list containing
    For each sample in buffer["samples"]:
        Add sample to new_samples
    Return AudioBuffer with:
        samples as new_samples
        channels as buffer["channels"]
        sample_rate as buffer["sample_rate"]
        length as buffer["length"]
        metadata as buffer["metadata"]

Process called "get_channel_samples" that takes buffer as AudioBuffer and channel as Integer returns List[AudioSample]:
    Let channel_samples be list containing
    Let channels be buffer["channels"]
    Let length be buffer["length"]
    For i from 0 to length minus 1:
        Let sample_index be i times channels plus channel
        Add buffer["samples"] at index sample_index to channel_samples
    Return channel_samples

Process called "set_channel_samples" that takes buffer as AudioBuffer and channel as Integer and samples as List[AudioSample] returns AudioBuffer:
    Let channels be buffer["channels"]
    Let length be buffer["length"]
    For i from 0 to length minus 1:
        If i is less than length of samples:
            Let sample_index be i times channels plus channel
            Set buffer["samples"] at index sample_index to samples at index i
    Return buffer

Process called "mix_buffers" that takes buffer1 as AudioBuffer and buffer2 as AudioBuffer and ratio as Float returns AudioBuffer:
    Let result be copy_audio_buffer with buffer as buffer1
    Let min_length be minimum of buffer1["length"] and buffer2["length"]
    Let channels be minimum of buffer1["channels"] and buffer2["channels"]
    
    For ch from 0 to channels minus 1:
        For i from 0 to min_length minus 1:
            Let index be i times channels plus ch
            Let sample1 be result["samples"] at index index
            Let sample2 be buffer2["samples"] at index index
            Let mixed_sample be sample1 times (1.0 minus ratio) plus sample2 times ratio
            Set result["samples"] at index index to mixed_sample
    
    Return result

Note: Filter Design and Implementation
Type called "IIRFilter":
    coefficients_a as List[Float]
    coefficients_b as List[Float]
    delay_line as List[Float]
    order as Integer
    type as FilterType
    frequency as Float
    q_factor as Float
    gain as Float

Process called "create_biquad_filter" that takes type as FilterType and frequency as Float and sample_rate as Float and q as Float and gain as Float returns IIRFilter:
    Let w be TWO_PI times frequency divided by sample_rate
    Let cos_w be cosine of w
    Let sin_w be sine of w
    Let alpha be sin_w divided by (2.0 times q)
    Let a be gain divided by 20.0
    Let s be sine of a times LOG_10 divided by 2.0
    
    Let b0 be 0.0
    Let b1 be 0.0
    Let b2 be 0.0
    Let a0 be 1.0 plus alpha
    Let a1 be negative 2.0 times cos_w
    Let a2 be 1.0 minus alpha
    
    Match type:
        When LOW_PASS:
            Set b0 to (1.0 minus cos_w) divided by 2.0
            Set b1 to 1.0 minus cos_w
            Set b2 to (1.0 minus cos_w) divided by 2.0
        
        When HIGH_PASS:
            Set b0 to (1.0 plus cos_w) divided by 2.0
            Set b1 to negative (1.0 plus cos_w)
            Set b2 to (1.0 plus cos_w) divided by 2.0
        
        When BAND_PASS:
            Set b0 to alpha
            Set b1 to 0.0
            Set b2 to negative alpha
        
        When NOTCH:
            Set b0 to 1.0
            Set b1 to negative 2.0 times cos_w
            Set b2 to 1.0
        
        When PEAK:
            Set b0 to 1.0 plus alpha times s
            Set b1 to negative 2.0 times cos_w
            Set b2 to 1.0 minus alpha times s
            Set a0 to 1.0 plus alpha divided by s
            Set a2 to 1.0 minus alpha divided by s
        
        When LOW_SHELF:
            Let beta be square_root of gain divided by q
            Set b0 to gain times ((gain plus 1.0) minus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w plus beta times sin_w)
            Set b1 to 2.0 times gain times ((gain minus 1.0) minus (gain plus 1.0) times cos_w)
            Set b2 to gain times ((gain plus 1.0) minus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w minus beta times sin_w)
            Set a0 to (gain plus 1.0) plus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w plus beta times sin_w
            Set a1 to negative 2.0 times ((gain minus 1.0) plus (gain plus 1.0) times cos_w)
            Set a2 to (gain plus 1.0) plus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w minus beta times sin_w
        
        When HIGH_SHELF:
            Let beta be square_root of gain divided by q
            Set b0 to gain times ((gain plus 1.0) plus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w plus beta times sin_w)
            Set b1 to negative 2.0 times gain times ((gain minus 1.0) plus (gain plus 1.0) times cos_w)
            Set b2 to gain times ((gain plus 1.0) plus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w minus beta times sin_w)
            Set a0 to (gain plus 1.0) minus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w plus beta times sin_w
            Set a1 to 2.0 times ((gain minus 1.0) minus (gain plus 1.0) times cos_w)
            Set a2 to (gain plus 1.0) minus (gain minus 1.0) times cos_w minus beta times sin_w
    
    Note: Normalize coefficients
    Set b0 to b0 divided by a0
    Set b1 to b1 divided by a0
    Set b2 to b2 divided by a0
    Set a1 to a1 divided by a0
    Set a2 to a2 divided by a0
    
    Return IIRFilter with:
        coefficients_a as list containing 1.0, a1, a2
        coefficients_b as list containing b0, b1, b2
        delay_line as list containing 0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 0.0
        order as 2
        type as type
        frequency as frequency
        q_factor as q
        gain as gain

Process called "apply_biquad_filter" that takes filter as IIRFilter and input as AudioSample returns AudioSample:
    Note: Direct Form II implementation for efficiency
    Let w be input minus filter["coefficients_a"] at index 1 times filter["delay_line"] at index 0 minus filter["coefficients_a"] at index 2 times filter["delay_line"] at index 1
    Let output be filter["coefficients_b"] at index 0 times w plus filter["coefficients_b"] at index 1 times filter["delay_line"] at index 0 plus filter["coefficients_b"] at index 2 times filter["delay_line"] at index 1
    
    Note: Update delay line
    Set filter["delay_line"] at index 1 to filter["delay_line"] at index 0
    Set filter["delay_line"] at index 0 to w
    
    Return output

Process called "process_filter" that takes filter as IIRFilter and buffer as AudioBuffer returns AudioProcessingResult:
    Let result_buffer be copy_audio_buffer with buffer as buffer
    Let channels be buffer["channels"]
    Let length be buffer["length"]
    
    For ch from 0 to channels minus 1:
        For i from 0 to length minus 1:
            Let sample_index be i times channels plus ch
            Let input_sample be buffer["samples"] at index sample_index
            Let filtered_sample be apply_biquad_filter with filter as filter and input as input_sample
            Set result_buffer["samples"] at index sample_index to filtered_sample
    
    Return ProcessingSuccess with buffer as result_buffer

Note: Delay-Based Effects
Type called "DelayLine":
    buffer as List[AudioSample]
    size as Integer
    write_pos as Integer
    read_pos as Integer

Process called "create_delay_line" that takes max_delay_samples as Integer returns DelayLine:
    Let buffer be list containing
    For i from 0 to max_delay_samples minus 1:
        Add 0.0 to buffer
    Return DelayLine with:
        buffer as buffer
        size as max_delay_samples
        write_pos as 0
        read_pos as 0

Process called "write_delay_sample" that takes delay as DelayLine and sample as AudioSample returns DelayLine:
    Set delay["buffer"] at index delay["write_pos"] to sample
    Set delay["write_pos"] to (delay["write_pos"] plus 1) modulo delay["size"]
    Return delay

Process called "read_delay_sample" that takes delay as DelayLine and delay_samples as Integer returns AudioSample:
    Let read_index be (delay["write_pos"] minus delay_samples plus delay["size"]) modulo delay["size"]
    Return delay["buffer"] at index read_index

Process called "read_delay_interpolated" that takes delay as DelayLine and delay_samples as Float returns AudioSample:
    Let delay_int be integer from delay_samples
    Let delay_frac be delay_samples minus delay_int
    
    Let sample1 be read_delay_sample with delay as delay and delay_samples as delay_int
    Let sample2 be read_delay_sample with delay as delay and delay_samples as delay_int plus 1
    
    Return sample1 times (1.0 minus delay_frac) plus sample2 times delay_frac

Note: Reverb Implementation (Schroeder Reverb)
Type called "Reverb":
    comb_filters as List[DelayLine]
    comb_gains as List[Float]
    allpass_filters as List[DelayLine]
    allpass_gains as List[Float]
    wet_gain as Float
    dry_gain as Float
    room_size as Float
    damping as Float

Process called "create_reverb" that takes sample_rate as Float and room_size as Float and damping as Float returns Reverb:
    Note: Comb filter delays (in samples) for different room sizes
    Let base_delays be list containing 1557, 1617, 1491, 1422, 1277, 1356, 1188, 1116
    Let allpass_delays be list containing 225, 556, 441, 341
    
    Let comb_filters be list containing
    Let comb_gains be list containing
    For each delay in base_delays:
        Let scaled_delay be integer from (delay times room_size)
        Add create_delay_line with max_delay_samples as scaled_delay to comb_filters
        Add 0.84 to comb_gains
    
    Let allpass_filters be list containing
    Let allpass_gains be list containing
    For each delay in allpass_delays:
        Let scaled_delay be integer from (delay times room_size)
        Add create_delay_line with max_delay_samples as scaled_delay to allpass_filters
        Add 0.7 to allpass_gains
    
    Return Reverb with:
        comb_filters as comb_filters
        comb_gains as comb_gains
        allpass_filters as allpass_filters
        allpass_gains as allpass_gains
        wet_gain as 0.3
        dry_gain as 0.7
        room_size as room_size
        damping as damping

Process called "process_reverb_sample" that takes reverb as Reverb and input as AudioSample returns AudioSample:
    Let comb_sum be 0.0
    
    Note: Process through comb filters
    For i from 0 to length of reverb["comb_filters"] minus 1:
        Let comb_filter be reverb["comb_filters"] at index i
        Let comb_gain be reverb["comb_gains"] at index i
        Let delay_samples be comb_filter["size"] minus 1
        Let delayed_sample be read_delay_sample with delay as comb_filter and delay_samples as delay_samples
        Let filtered_sample be input plus delayed_sample times comb_gain times reverb["damping"]
        Let comb_filter be write_delay_sample with delay as comb_filter and sample as filtered_sample
        Set comb_sum to comb_sum plus delayed_sample
    
    Note: Process through allpass filters
    Let allpass_output be comb_sum
    For i from 0 to length of reverb["allpass_filters"] minus 1:
        Let allpass_filter be reverb["allpass_filters"] at index i
        Let allpass_gain be reverb["allpass_gains"] at index i
        Let delay_samples be allpass_filter["size"] minus 1
        Let delayed_sample be read_delay_sample with delay as allpass_filter and delay_samples as delay_samples
        Let filtered_input be allpass_output plus delayed_sample times allpass_gain
        Let allpass_filter be write_delay_sample with delay as allpass_filter and sample as filtered_input
        Set allpass_output to delayed_sample minus allpass_output times allpass_gain
    
    Return input times reverb["dry_gain"] plus allpass_output times reverb["wet_gain"]

Note: Compressor/Limiter (Industry-Standard Implementation)
Type called "Compressor":
    threshold as Float
    ratio as Float
    attack_time as Float
    release_time as Float
    knee_width as Float
    makeup_gain as Float
    mode as CompressorMode
    envelope_follower as Float
    gain_reduction as Float
    attack_coeff as Float
    release_coeff as Float
    sample_rate as Float

Process called "create_compressor" that takes threshold as Float and ratio as Float and attack_ms as Float and release_ms as Float and sample_rate as Float returns Compressor:
    Let attack_coeff be exponential of (-1.0 divided by (attack_ms times 0.001 times sample_rate))
    Let release_coeff be exponential of (-1.0 divided by (release_ms times 0.001 times sample_rate))
    
    Return Compressor with:
        threshold as threshold
        ratio as ratio
        attack_time as attack_ms
        release_time as release_ms
        knee_width as 2.0
        makeup_gain as 0.0
        mode as RMS
        envelope_follower as 0.0
        gain_reduction as 0.0
        attack_coeff as attack_coeff
        release_coeff as release_coeff
        sample_rate as sample_rate

Process called "process_compressor_sample" that takes compressor as Compressor and input as AudioSample returns AudioSample:
    Note: Envelope detection
    Let input_level be absolute_value of input
    Match compressor["mode"]:
        When RMS:
            Set input_level to square_root of (input times input)
        When PEAK:
            Set input_level to absolute_value of input
    
    Note: Envelope follower with attack/release
    If input_level is greater than compressor["envelope_follower"]:
        Set compressor["envelope_follower"] to input_level times (1.0 minus compressor["attack_coeff"]) plus compressor["envelope_follower"] times compressor["attack_coeff"]
    Otherwise:
        Set compressor["envelope_follower"] to input_level times (1.0 minus compressor["release_coeff"]) plus compressor["envelope_follower"] times compressor["release_coeff"]
    
    Note: Gain reduction calculation
    Let envelope_db be 20.0 times log10 of (compressor["envelope_follower"] plus 0.000001)
    Let threshold_db be compressor["threshold"]
    Let gain_reduction_db be 0.0
    
    If envelope_db is greater than threshold_db:
        Let over_threshold be envelope_db minus threshold_db
        Set gain_reduction_db to over_threshold times (1.0 minus 1.0 divided by compressor["ratio"])
    
    Note: Soft knee implementation
    Let knee_half be compressor["knee_width"] divided by 2.0
    If envelope_db is greater than (threshold_db minus knee_half) and envelope_db is less than (threshold_db plus knee_half):
        Let knee_ratio be (envelope_db minus threshold_db plus knee_half) divided by compressor["knee_width"]
        Set gain_reduction_db to gain_reduction_db times knee_ratio times knee_ratio
    
    Set compressor["gain_reduction"] to gain_reduction_db
    
    Note: Apply gain reduction and makeup gain
    Let gain_linear be power of 10.0 and (negative gain_reduction_db plus compressor["makeup_gain"]) divided by 20.0
    Return input times gain_linear

Note: Chorus Effect
Type called "Chorus":
    delay_lines as List[DelayLine]
    lfo_phases as List[Float]
    lfo_rates as List[Float]
    delay_times as List[Float]
    depth as Float
    mix as Float
    voices as Integer
    sample_rate as Float

Process called "create_chorus" that takes voices as Integer and rate_hz as Float and depth_ms as Float and mix as Float and sample_rate as Float returns Chorus:
    Let max_delay_samples be integer from (depth_ms times 0.001 times sample_rate times 2.0)
    Let delay_lines be list containing
    Let lfo_phases be list containing
    Let lfo_rates be list containing
    Let delay_times be list containing
    
    For i from 0 to voices minus 1:
        Add create_delay_line with max_delay_samples as max_delay_samples to delay_lines
        Add (TWO_PI times i) divided by voices to lfo_phases
        Add rate_hz times (1.0 plus i times 0.1) to lfo_rates
        Add depth_ms times 0.001 times sample_rate to delay_times
    
    Return Chorus with:
        delay_lines as delay_lines
        lfo_phases as lfo_phases
        lfo_rates as lfo_rates
        delay_times as delay_times
        depth as depth_ms
        mix as mix
        voices as voices
        sample_rate as sample_rate

Process called "process_chorus_sample" that takes chorus as Chorus and input as AudioSample returns AudioSample:
    Let output_sum be 0.0
    
    For i from 0 to chorus["voices"] minus 1:
        Note: Update LFO phase
        Set chorus["lfo_phases"] at index i to chorus["lfo_phases"] at index i plus TWO_PI times chorus["lfo_rates"] at index i divided by chorus["sample_rate"]
        If chorus["lfo_phases"] at index i is greater than TWO_PI:
            Set chorus["lfo_phases"] at index i to chorus["lfo_phases"] at index i minus TWO_PI
        
        Note: Calculate modulated delay time
        Let lfo_value be sine of chorus["lfo_phases"] at index i
        Let modulated_delay be chorus["delay_times"] at index i times (1.0 plus lfo_value times 0.5)
        
        Note: Write input to delay line
        Let delay_line be chorus["delay_lines"] at index i
        Let delay_line be write_delay_sample with delay as delay_line and sample as input
        
        Note: Read delayed sample with interpolation
        Let delayed_sample be read_delay_interpolated with delay as delay_line and delay_samples as modulated_delay
        Set output_sum to output_sum plus delayed_sample
    
    Let chorus_output be output_sum divided by chorus["voices"]
    Return input times (1.0 minus chorus["mix"]) plus chorus_output times chorus["mix"]

Note: Distortion Effects
Process called "apply_soft_clipping" that takes input as AudioSample and drive as Float returns AudioSample:
    Let driven_signal be input times drive
    If absolute_value of driven_signal is less than or equal to 1.0:
        Return driven_signal
    Otherwise:
        If driven_signal is greater than 0.0:
            Return 2.0 divided by 3.0
        Otherwise:
            Return negative 2.0 divided by 3.0

Process called "apply_tube_saturation" that takes input as AudioSample and drive as Float and bias as Float returns AudioSample:
    Let biased_input be input plus bias
    Let driven_signal be biased_input times drive
    Let saturated be driven_signal divided by (1.0 plus absolute_value of driven_signal)
    Return saturated minus bias

Process called "apply_waveshaping" that takes input as AudioSample and shape as Float returns AudioSample:
    Let shaped_signal be input times (1.0 plus shape)
    Return shaped_signal divided by (1.0 plus shape times absolute_value of input)

Note: Spectral Processing (FFT-based effects)
Type called "FFTProcessor":
    fft_size as Integer
    window as List[Float]
    overlap as Float
    input_buffer as List[AudioSample]
    output_buffer as List[AudioSample]
    analysis_buffer as List[Complex]
    synthesis_buffer as List[Complex]

Type called "Complex":
    real as Float
    imaginary as Float

Process called "create_fft_processor" that takes fft_size as Integer and window_type as WindowType and overlap as Float returns FFTProcessor:
    Let window be create_window with size as fft_size and type as window_type
    Let input_buffer be list containing
    Let output_buffer be list containing
    For i from 0 to fft_size minus 1:
        Add 0.0 to input_buffer
        Add 0.0 to output_buffer
    
    Let analysis_buffer be list containing
    Let synthesis_buffer be list containing
    For i from 0 to fft_size minus 1:
        Add Complex with real as 0.0 and imaginary as 0.0 to analysis_buffer
        Add Complex with real as 0.0 and imaginary as 0.0 to synthesis_buffer
    
    Return FFTProcessor with:
        fft_size as fft_size
        window as window
        overlap as overlap
        input_buffer as input_buffer
        output_buffer as output_buffer
        analysis_buffer as analysis_buffer
        synthesis_buffer as synthesis_buffer

Process called "create_window" that takes size as Integer and type as WindowType returns List[Float]:
    Let window be list containing
    For i from 0 to size minus 1:
        Let n be i divided by (size minus 1)
        Let window_value be 1.0
        
        Match type:
            When HANNING:
                Set window_value to 0.5 times (1.0 minus cosine of TWO_PI times n)
            When HAMMING:
                Set window_value to 0.54 minus 0.46 times cosine of TWO_PI times n
            When BLACKMAN:
                Set window_value to 0.42 minus 0.5 times cosine of TWO_PI times n plus 0.08 times cosine of 4.0 times 3.14159 times n
            When RECTANGULAR:
                Set window_value to 1.0
            When TRIANGULAR:
                If n is less than 0.5:
                    Set window_value to 2.0 times n
                Otherwise:
                    Set window_value to 2.0 times (1.0 minus n)
        
        Add window_value to window
    
    Return window

Note: Parametric EQ (Multi-band)
Type called "ParametricEQ":
    bands as List[IIRFilter]
    frequencies as List[Float]
    gains as List[Float]
    q_factors as List[Float]
    enabled as List[Boolean]

Process called "create_parametric_eq" that takes num_bands as Integer and sample_rate as Float returns ParametricEQ:
    Let bands be list containing
    Let frequencies be list containing
    Let gains be list containing
    Let q_factors be list containing
    Let enabled be list containing
    
    For i from 0 to num_bands minus 1:
        Let frequency be 1000.0 times power of 2.0 and (i minus num_bands divided by 2) divided by 2.0
        Add create_biquad_filter with type as PEAK and frequency as frequency and sample_rate as sample_rate and q as 1.0 and gain as 1.0 to bands
        Add frequency to frequencies
        Add 0.0 to gains
        Add 1.0 to q_factors
        Add true to enabled
    
    Return ParametricEQ with:
        bands as bands
        frequencies as frequencies
        gains as gains
        q_factors as q_factors
        enabled as enabled

Process called "update_eq_band" that takes eq as ParametricEQ and band_index as Integer and frequency as Float and gain_db as Float and q_factor as Float and sample_rate as Float returns ParametricEQ:
    If band_index is greater than or equal to 0 and band_index is less than length of eq["bands"]:
        Set eq["frequencies"] at index band_index to frequency
        Set eq["gains"] at index band_index to gain_db
        Set eq["q_factors"] at index band_index to q_factor
        
        Let gain_linear be power of 10.0 and gain_db divided by 20.0
        Let new_filter be create_biquad_filter with type as PEAK and frequency as frequency and sample_rate as sample_rate and q as q_factor and gain as gain_linear
        Set eq["bands"] at index band_index to new_filter
    
    Return eq

Process called "process_parametric_eq" that takes eq as ParametricEQ and buffer as AudioBuffer returns AudioProcessingResult:
    Let result_buffer be copy_audio_buffer with buffer as buffer
    
    For i from 0 to length of eq["bands"] minus 1:
        If eq["enabled"] at index i:
            Let filter_result be process_filter with filter as eq["bands"] at index i and buffer as result_buffer
            Match filter_result:
                When ProcessingSuccess with buffer as filtered_buffer:
                    Set result_buffer to filtered_buffer
                When ProcessingError with message as msg:
                    Return ProcessingError with message as msg and code as "EQ_PROCESSING_ERROR"
    
    Return ProcessingSuccess with buffer as result_buffer

Note: Advanced Effect Chain Processing
Type called "EffectChain":
    effects as List[AudioEffect]
    bypass_all as Boolean
    input_gain as Float
    output_gain as Float
    parallel_processing as Boolean

Process called "create_effect_chain" returns EffectChain:
    Return EffectChain with:
        effects as list containing
        bypass_all as false
        input_gain as 1.0
        output_gain as 1.0
        parallel_processing as false

Process called "add_effect_to_chain" that takes chain as EffectChain and effect as AudioEffect returns EffectChain:
    Add effect to chain["effects"]
    Return chain

Process called "process_effect_chain" that takes chain as EffectChain and buffer as AudioBuffer returns AudioProcessingResult:
    If chain["bypass_all"]:
        Return ProcessingSuccess with buffer as buffer
    
    Let result_buffer be copy_audio_buffer with buffer as buffer
    
    Note: Apply input gain
    For i from 0 to length of result_buffer["samples"] minus 1:
        Set result_buffer["samples"] at index i to result_buffer["samples"] at index i times chain["input_gain"]
    
    Note: Process each effect in the chain
    For each effect in chain["effects"]:
        If effect["enabled"] and not effect["bypass"]:
            Note: Here we would call the specific effect processing function
            Note: This is a framework - specific effects would be plugged in here
            Continue
    
    Note: Apply output gain
    For i from 0 to length of result_buffer["samples"] minus 1:
        Set result_buffer["samples"] at index i to result_buffer["samples"] at index i times chain["output_gain"]
    
    Return ProcessingSuccess with buffer as result_buffer

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "db_to_linear" that takes db as Float returns Float:
    Return power of 10.0 and db divided by 20.0

Process called "linear_to_db" that takes linear as Float returns Float:
    Return 20.0 times log10 of (absolute_value of linear plus 0.000001)

Process called "frequency_to_midi" that takes frequency as Float returns Float:
    Return 69.0 plus 12.0 times log2 of (frequency divided by 440.0)

Process called "midi_to_frequency" that takes midi_note as Float returns Float:
    Return 440.0 times power of 2.0 and (midi_note minus 69.0) divided by 12.0

Process called "calculate_rms" that takes samples as List[AudioSample] returns Float:
    Let sum_squares be 0.0
    For each sample in samples:
        Set sum_squares to sum_squares plus sample times sample
    Return square_root of (sum_squares divided by length of samples)

Process called "calculate_peak" that takes samples as List[AudioSample] returns Float:
    Let peak be 0.0
    For each sample in samples:
        Let abs_sample be absolute_value of sample
        If abs_sample is greater than peak:
            Set peak to abs_sample
    Return peak

Process called "normalize_buffer" that takes buffer as AudioBuffer and target_level as Float returns AudioBuffer:
    Let current_peak be calculate_peak with samples as buffer["samples"]
    If current_peak is greater than 0.000001:
        Let gain be target_level divided by current_peak
        For i from 0 to length of buffer["samples"] minus 1:
            Set buffer["samples"] at index i to buffer["samples"] at index i times gain
    Return buffer

Note: Mathematical Helper Functions
Process called "log10" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm divided by ln(10)
    Return natural_log of x divided by LOG_10

Process called "log2" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm divided by ln(2)
    Return natural_log of x divided by 0.6931471805599453

Process called "power" that takes base as Float and exponent as Float returns Float:
    Note: e^(exponent * ln(base))
    Return exponential of (exponent times natural_log of base)

Process called "sine" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Taylor series approximation for sine
    Let result be x
    Let term be x
    For i from 1 to 10:
        Set term to negative term times x times x divided by ((2 times i) times (2 times i plus 1))
        Set result to result plus term
    Return result

Process called "cosine" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: cos(x) = sin(x + π/2)
    Return sine of (x plus 1.5707963267948966)

Process called "square_root" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Newton's method for square root
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    Let guess be x divided by 2.0
    For i from 1 to 10:
        Set guess to (guess plus x divided by guess) divided by 2.0
    Return guess

Process called "absolute_value" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Return negative x
    Otherwise:
        Return x

Process called "exponential" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Taylor series for e^x
    Let result be 1.0
    Let term be 1.0
    For i from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times x divided by i
        Set result to result plus term
    Return result

Process called "natural_log" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm using series expansion
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return negative 1000.0
    If x is equal to 1.0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let y be (x minus 1.0) divided by (x plus 1.0)
    Let y_squared be y times y
    Let result be y
    Let term be y
    
    For i from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times y_squared
        Set result to result plus term divided by (2 times i plus 1)
    
    Return 2.0 times result

Process called "minimum" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    If a is less than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "maximum" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    If a is greater than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b